Writing universal libraries using C++ and consuming it in Rust (WASI)

B Shyam Sundar
4 min read
·
Jun 4, 2023

Using Wasmer for creating a Universal Library

Introduction

In this blog, we will explore how to create a WebAssembly (WASM) library using C++ with the help of Wasmer, a popular WASM runtime, and use the web assembly module in Rust (console binary) using Web Assembly System Interface (WASI). For the sake of simplicity we will create a simple “add” function that takes two integers as inputs and returns their sum.

Prerequisites

This article you would need the following:

  1. WasiEnv
  2. Rust

Introduction to WebAssembly

Shameless self promotion plug: You can read my earlier blogs on WebAssembly here.

Briefly, WebAssembly is a binary instruction format that is designed to be a low-level virtual machine that runs code at near-native speed in web browsers. It is not specific to the web and can be run on other platforms as well. WebAssembly code can be compiled from various programming languages such as C, C++, Rust, C#, and more.

Wasmer

Wasmer is a lightweight and fast WebAssembly runtime that can run WebAssembly modules on a variety of platforms, including Windows, Linux, and macOS. Wasmer supports multiple programming languages, including C, C++, Rust, and more.

Creating a WebAssembly Library using C++

First, we will create a simple “add” function using C++ that takes two integers as inputs and returns their sum.

// add.cpp

extern "C" {
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

From this code we will use the add function in Rust.

Get B Shyam Sundar’s stories in your inbox

Join Medium for free to get updates from this writer.

The extern “C” is utilised so that he function “add” is not mangled by the compiler. We will have to use the same name in our Rust code.

Here’s the updated command to compile the code to WebAssembly:

wasmc++ add.cpp -o add.wasm

Once this finishes execution, you should be able to able see the file add.wasm. We will load this web assembly into our Rust project.

Using it in Rust

Let us create a simple Rust project using

cargo new wasmer-consume

Add the following dependency in Cargo.toml

wasmer = "3.1.1"
wasmer-wasi = "3.1.1"

Replace the following code in main.rs

use wasmer::{Instance, Module, Store, Value, Function};
use wasmer_wasi::{WasiState, WasiEnv, generate_import_object_from_env, WasiFunctionEnv};

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    // Read the WebAssembly module bytes
    let wasm_bytes = include_bytes!("/Users/shyamsundarb/Library/cppWrk/wasmerblog/wasmer-consume/add.wasm");
    
    // Create a new store to hold WebAssembly instances
    let mut store = Store::default();

    // Create a new WASI state for the WASI environment
    let wasi_state = WasiState::new("wasi_snapshot_preview1").build()?;
    
    // Create a new WASI environment using the WASI state
    let wasi_env = WasiEnv::new(wasi_state);

    // Compile the WebAssembly module from the provided bytes
    let module = Module::new(&store, wasm_bytes)?;

    // Create a new instance of the WASI functions using the store and WASI environment
    let wasi_func = WasiFunctionEnv::new(&mut store, wasi_env);

    // Generate the import object from the WASI functions and environment
    let mut import_object = generate_import_object_from_env(&mut store, &wasi_func.env, wasmer_wasi::WasiVersion::Latest);
    
    // Create a host function that exits the program
    let exit_func = Function::new_typed(&mut store, |i: i32| {
        std::process::exit(i);
    });

    // Add the missing `proc_exit` function to the import object
    import_object.define("wasi_snapshot_preview1", "proc_exit", exit_func);
    
    // Create a new instance of the WebAssembly module with the import object
    let instance = Instance::new(&mut store, &module, &import_object)?;

    // Get the `add` function from the instance exports
    let add: &Function = instance.exports.get_function("add")?;

    // Call the `add` function with two integer arguments
    let result = add.call(&mut store, &[Value::I32(2), Value::I32(3)])?;
    
    // Retrieve the result value from the function call
    let result_value: i32 = result[0].unwrap_i32();

    // Print the result
    println!("Result: {}", result_value);

    Ok(())
}

I have inlined comments as to why each line is being used.

When you run `cargo run` command, if all went well you should see the following:

We can see that the function is usable in a console application. Now let us see how this can be utilised in the browser.

Conclusion

Though this very example is trivial, conceptually it opens up a new meaning for “write once, run everywhere”. Web assembly as a tech is still nascent. It helps us bridge the gap between programming languages and platform.

My experience when developing this that, the tech as impressive it is, the documentation of this stack certainly can be improved. I understand that, this being developed rapidly, the documentation tends to be unreliable due to frequent breaking changes.

Beyond that I look forward to how this tech evolves.
